class Solution {
    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        return validate(root , Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE);
        
    }
    // Recursive function to validate the BST
    private boolean validate(TreeNode node, long min, long max){
        // Base case: an empty node is valid
        if(node == null) return true;
        
        // If current node breaks the valid range rule
        if(node.val <= min || node.val >= max) return false;

        // Recursively check left and right subtrees
        return validate(node.left , min, node.val)&& validate(node.right, node.val, max);
    }
}



Explaination: 

ğŸŒ³ What is a Binary Search Tree (BST)?
In a valid BST, the following rules must be true for every node:

All nodes in the left subtree must have values less than the current nodeâ€™s value.

All nodes in the right subtree must have values greater than the current nodeâ€™s value.

Both left and right subtrees must also be valid BSTs.

ğŸ§  Intuition Behind the Algorithm
We use a helper function to keep track of a valid range for each node.

Initially, the root node is allowed to have any value, so the range is (-âˆ to +âˆ).

When we go to the left child, we update the max limit to be the current nodeâ€™s value.

When we go to the right child, we update the min limit to be the current nodeâ€™s value.

If any nodeâ€™s value falls outside the allowed range, it's not a BST.

âœ… Step-by-step Example
Valid BST Example:
markdown
Copy code
      10
     /  \
    5   15
       /  \
      11  20
Here's how we validate it:

Start at root 10: valid range (-âˆ, âˆ)

Go left to 5: range (-âˆ, 10) âœ…

Go right to 15: range (10, âˆ) âœ…

15's left child 11: range (10, 15) âœ…

15's right child 20: range (15, âˆ) âœ…

ğŸ‘‰ All nodes are within valid ranges â€” so this is a valid BST.

âŒ Invalid BST Example:
markdown
Copy code
      5
     / \
    1   4
       / \
      3   6
This looks okay at first, but:

4 is on the right of 5 â†’ should be greater than 5

But 4 is less than 5 â†’ âŒ This breaks the rule.

So this is not a valid BST.

âœ… Java Code (with Explanation)
java
Copy code
class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left, right;
    TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
}

public class Solution {
    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
        return validate(root, Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE);
    }

    // Recursive function to validate the BST
    private boolean validate(TreeNode node, long min, long max) {
        // Base case: an empty node is valid
        if (node == null) return true;

        // If current node breaks the valid range rule
        if (node.val <= min || node.val >= max) return false;

        // Recursively check left and right subtrees
        return validate(node.left, min, node.val) &&
               validate(node.right, node.val, max);
    }
}
ğŸ§® Time and Space Complexity
Time Complexity: O(n) â†’ We visit each node once.

Space Complexity: O(h) â†’ h is the height of the tree (recursive call stack).

